Noise 2
Review
  • We discussed coherent noise last time
  • Input: 1D, 2D, or 3D point
  • Output: “Random” value between -1 and 1
    • Varies smoothly as input value changes
    • Always get same output for same input
Applications
  • What can we do with noise?
  • Lots of ideas. We’ll look at a few examples…
  • Your creativity should suggest lots of additional possibilities, though!
Radar
  • Old style radar display
  • Problem: It looks like a triangle spinning around (because it is!)
Radar
  • Add some noise: (Notice the Mach banding, though!)
float f = noise( gl_FragCoord.xy * 0.1 );
f = smoothstep( -0.5, 0.5, f );
float shift = 0.90;
f = (f * (1.0-shift) + shift );
color = texture(tex, vec3( v_texcoord, 0.0) );
color.rgb *= f;
  • Result
Dissolve
  • Make object dissolve
float n = noise(gl_FragCoord.xy * 0.1 );
n += 1.0;
n *= 0.5;
color.a = step( time, n ) * basecolor.a;
  • Result
Dissolve
  • Add yellow highlight around dissolving areas
float n = noise(gl_FragCoord.xy * 0.1 );
n += 1.0; n *= 0.5;
float hilitemix = smoothstep( time, time+0.1, n );
color.rgb = diffuse * basecolor.rgb + emissioncolor.rgb;
color.rgb = mix( vec3(1, 1, 0), color.rgb, hilitemix );
color.a = step( time, n ) * basecolor.a;
Procedural Textures
  • Idea: Instead of obtaining texture from an image, compute mathematically
    • Benefit: Less memory usage
    • Benefit: Memory bandwidth often bottleneck on modern GPU’s
    • Benefit: Never gets blocky, no matter how close we look
Camo
  • Really simple application: If noise value < 0: Choose one color; else, choose another
  • VS needs to pass object space position to FS:
layout(location=0) in vec3 position;
...other declarations...
out vec3 v_objPos;
void main(){
    v_objPos = position;
    ...rest of code as usual...
}
Camo
  • FS:
void main(){
    vec3 p = v_objPos * 8.0;
    float n = noise( p ) ;
    if( n < 0 )
        color = vec4(0.1, 0.3, 0.15, 1);
    else
        color = vec4(0.1, 0.8, 0.15, 1);
    ...apply lighting as usual...
}
Results
  • Ogre mesh by Keenan Crane
Marble
  • A bit more complex: A marble texture
  • First, Define a color ramp texture like so:
Marble
  • Use the noise to modulate where we sample in the texture
  • Fragment shader:
vec3 p = v_objPos * 8.0;    //object space position
float n = noise( p )    //3D noise; n=-1...1
n = n * 0.5;            //n=-0.5 ... 0.5
n = n + 0.5;            //n=0...1
color = texture(tex, vec3(n, 0.5, 0) );
...apply lighting as usual...
Results
  • The result looks a bit like marble, but it’s unconvincing
  • Ogre model by Keenan Crane
Improvement
  • We can improve appearance by using several octaves of noise
    • Sometimes called turbulence
  • One octave of noise: n = noise( p )
  • Two octaves: n = noise(p) + 0.5 * noise(p*2)
  • Three octaves: n = noise(p) + 0.5 * noise(p*2) + 0.25 * noise(p*4)
Result
  • If we apply three octaves of noise when computing the marble: Appearance gains more visual complexity
vec3 p = v_objPos * 8.0;    //object space position
float n = n = noise(p) + 0.5 * noise(p*2) + 0.25 * noise(p*4);
n = n * 0.5;
n = n + 0.5;
color = texture(tex, vec3(n, 0.5, 0) );
...apply lighting as usual...
Result
Fire
  • An example of using noise to animate an effect
  • This works well with billboards
  • Idea: We have a quad with texture coordinates in range 0…1
  • We also define a texture like so:
Fire
  • If we just textured the billboard with the texture, it would give us a static flame
  • Albeit one that looks like it’s in a windless environment
  • Real fire has visual complexity
    • And we want to animate it
  • Perhaps we can use noise to help here
Link

Fire

vec2 p = v_texcoord;
p += 0.5*noise(p);
color = texture(tex, vec3(p, 0.0));
  • Result: (For now, don’t worry about the texture wrapping)
Fire
  • We’re getting some visual complexity
  • What if we tweak our shader a bit?
vec2 p = v_texcoord;
p += 0.5*noise(p*4.0);
color = texture(tex, vec3(p, 0.0));
  • Looks a bit more fire-like
Fire
  • Let’s go back to the turbulence idea:
vec2 p = v_texcoord;
float n = noise(p);
n += 0.5*noise(p*2.0);
n += 0.25*noise(p*4.0);
color = texture(tex, vec3( p + vec2(n), 0 ) );
  • Ugh.
Fire
  • It looks like we’re influencing the texture coordinate too much
  • Let’s scale the amount down a bit
vec2 p = v_texcoord;
float n = noise(p);
n += 0.5*noise(p*2.0);
n += 0.25*noise(p*4.0);
n *= 0.4;
color = texture(tex, vec3( p + vec2(n), 0 ) );
Fire
  • Maybe if we boost the frequency of the thing being passed into noise() we’d get more small-scale structure
vec2 p = v_texcoord;
vec2 p_ = p*16.0;
float n = noise(p_);
n += 0.5*noise(p_*2.0);
n += 0.25*noise(p_*4.0);
n *= 0.4;
color = texture(tex, vec3( p + vec2(n), 0 ) );
  • Yes! (But now there’s too much variation in texture coordinates)
Fire
  • Adjust the multiplier on n to be smaller
vec2 p = v_texcoord;
vec2 p_ = p*16.0;
float n = noise(p_);
n += 0.5*noise(p_*2.0);
n += 0.25*noise(p_*4.0);
n *= 0.1;
color = texture(tex, vec3( p + vec2(n), 0 ) );
  • Much better!
Animation
  • Animation is important for fire
  • How to animate?
  • Assume we have a uniform called “time”
  • We add time to the y and z coordinates of p
    • Not as good if we just add to y coordinate
  • This is what we get: Link
vec3 p = vec3(v_texcoord.x, v_texcoord.y-time, time);
vec3 p_ = p*16.0;
float n = noise(p_);
n += 0.5*noise(p_*2.0);
n += 0.25*noise(p_*4.0);
n *= 0.1;
color = texture(tex, vec3( v_texcoord + vec2(n), 0 ) );

Fire 2
  • Another idea for fire: Based on Febucci (see references)
  • Begin with basic noise:
vec2 v = v_texcoord * 8.0;
float n = noise(v);
n = 0.5*(n + 1.0);
color = vec4(n, n, n, 1.0);
Fire 2
  • Alter the noise sampling according to time
vec2 v = v_texcoord * 8.0;
v.y -= time * 32.0;
float n = noise(v);
n = 0.5*(n + 1.0);
color = vec4(n, n, n, 1.0);
Fire 2
  • Now we want to threshold the noise according to the y coordinate
  • smoothstep( a, b, c )
    • If c < a: 0
    • If c > b: 1
    • Else, smooth ramp from 0 to 1
vec2 v = v_texcoord * 8.0;
v.y -= time * 32.0;
float n = noise(v);
n = 0.5*(n + 1.0);
float s = smoothstep( v_texcoord.y, 1.0, n );
s = 1.0 - s;
color = vec4(s, s, s, 1.0);
Fire 2
  • Use a ramp texture to select the color
vec2 v = v_texcoord * 8.0;
v.y -= time * 32.0;
float n = noise(v);
n = 0.5*(n + 1.0);
float s = smoothstep( v_texcoord.y, 1.0, n );
s = 1.0 - s;
color = texture( tex, vec3( s, 0.5, 0 ) );
Fire 2
  • Doesn’t seem to have much visual complexity. Let’s add some turbulence.
vec2 v = v_texcoord * 8.0;
v.y -= time * 32.0;
float n = noise(v);
n += 0.5 * noise(2.0*v);
n += 0.25 * noise(4.0*v);
n = 0.5*(n + 1.0);
float s = smoothstep( v_texcoord.y, 1.0, n );
s = 1.0 - s;
color = texture( tex, vec3( s, 0.5, 0 ) );
Fire 2
  • It’s a little too dark. Make it a bit brighter by changing the smoothstep()
vec2 v = v_texcoord * 8.0;
v.y -= time * 32.0;
float n = noise(v);
n += 0.5 * noise(2.0*v);
n += 0.25 * noise(4.0*v);
n = 0.5*(n + 1.0);
float s = smoothstep( v_texcoord.y - 0.25, 0.95, n );
s = 1.0 - s;
color = texture( tex, vec3( s, 0.5, 0 ) );
Fire 2
  • We’d like a little more contrast. We can get that by applying another smoothstep.
vec2 v = v_texcoord * 8.0;
v.y -= time * 32.0;
float n = noise(v);
n += 0.5 * noise(2.0*v);
n += 0.25 * noise(4.0*v);
n = 0.5*(n + 1.0);
float s = smoothstep( v_texcoord.y - 0.25, 0.95, n );
s = smoothstep(0.0, 1.0, s);
s = 1.0 - s;
color = texture( tex, vec3( s, 0.5, 0 ) );
Fire 2
  • The animation doesn’t look “turbulent” enough. Try using 3D noise
vec2 v = v_texcoord * 8.0;
v.y -= time * 32.0;
float n = noise( vec3(v, time*8.0) );
n += 0.5 * noise(2.0*v);
n += 0.25 * noise(4.0*v);
n = 0.5*(n + 1.0);
float s = smoothstep( v_texcoord.y - 0.25, 0.95, n );
s = smoothstep(0.0, 1.0, s);
s = 1.0 - s;
color = texture( tex, vec3( s, 0.5, 0 ) );
Fire 3
  • Presented without comment…Same basic idea as the previous one, but some more tweaks from additional experiments
  • Link
vec2 v = v_texcoord * 8.0;
color = texture( tex, vec3(v, 0) );
float T = time * 32.0;
vec3 noiseCoord = vec3(v.x, v.y-T, T*0.25 );
float nv = noise( noiseCoord );
nv += 0.5 * noise( 2.0*noiseCoord );
nv += 0.25 * noise( 4.0*noiseCoord );
nv = (nv + 1.0)*0.5;
float threshold = -0.1 + v_texcoord.y;
float s1 = smoothstep( threshold-0.2, threshold+0.2, nv );
float s2 = smoothstep( threshold-0.2, threshold+0.2, nv-0.15);
float s3 = smoothstep( threshold-0.2, threshold+0.2, nv-0.3);
float diff1 = s1-s2;
float diff2 = s2-s3;
float val1 = mix( diff1, 1.0, diff2 );
float t = mix( 0.0, 1.0, val1);
//avoid Intel wrapping bug: GPU Ignores texture clamp_to_edge
t = clamp(t, 0.01, 0.99);
vec3 texcoord = vec3(t, 0.5, 0);
color.rgb = texture( tex, texcoord ).rgb;
color.a = s1*s1;
1D Noise
  • What about 1D noise? Here’s an example: Lightning bolt
  • Create a line segment with, say, 128 vertices
    • Positions: x=0, y=0…1
    • Texture coordinates: x=0…1
  • Draw it:
    • glBindVertexArray(lineVao);
    • glDrawArrays(GL_LINE_STRIP, 0, 128)
1D Noise
  • VS uses 1D noise to perturb position (x coordinate), and time variable to give illusion of motion:
vec4 p = vec4(position, 1.0);
float nc = texcoord.x*4.0 + time;   //noise coordinate
float n = noise(nc);        //use three octaves of noise
n += 0.5 * noise(2*nc);
n += 0.25 * noise(4*nc);
n *= sign(noise(2.0*time)); //make it flip left-right randomly
p.x += 0.25 * n;
p = p * worldMatrix;
p = p * viewMatrix;
p = p * projMatrix;
gl_Position = p;
  • FS just outputs solid white
